nvestigate and Restart Shift Offer Pipeline","description":"With only 3 offers sent platform-wide, determine why offer volume is so low. Check whether automated offer workflows are configured and active for all Victoria sites. Manually trigger offers for all open shifts at Hyatt Hotel, Holiday Inn Express, and HOLIDAY INN VICTORIA immediately.","priority":"urgent","category":"Recruitment Pipeline"},{"title":"Victoria Market Worker Supply Assessment","description":"Conduct an immediate review of the available worker pool in the Victoria region. If qualified workers are insufficient to cover demand across 5 sites, initiate emergency recruitment — post job ads, activate referral programs, or engage staffing agency partners to supplement supply within 48-72 hours.","priority":"urgent","category":"Recruitment Pipeline"},{"title":"Review Shift Terms for Long-Open Positions","description":"For shifts open 14-30+ days with no fills (particularly Holiday Inn Express and HOLIDAY INN VICTORIA), review pay rates, shift hours, and location accessibility. If terms are below market or unattractive, adjust rates or restructure shifts to improve worker appeal before sending additional offers.","priority":"high","category":"Shift Optimization"},{"title":"Verify Data Completeness: Upcoming Shift Schedule","description":"The absence of any shifts in the next 48 hours combined with 0% fill rates across 30 days is anomalous. Confirm with site managers that upcoming shifts are being entered into the system. If scheduling is happening outside the platform, work to migrate it in to ensure accurate visibility.","priority":"high","category":"Data Integrity"},{"title":"Document and Replicate Skyward Building Practices","description":"Skyward Building achieved 100% fill rate while all other tracked sites are at 0%. Interview the Skyward manager or review their shift posting and offer practices to identify what is working — then apply those learnings to underperforming sites.","priority":"medium","category":"Best Practice Sharing"},{"title":"Establish Weekly Fill Rate Review Cadence","description":"Given that multiple sites have been at 0% fill rate for 30+ days without apparent escalation, implement a weekly executive review of fill rate trends. Set automated alerts for any site falling below a defined threshold (e.g., 70%) for more than 7 consecutive days.","priority":"medium","category":"Governance"},{"title":"Payroll Risk Assessment for Unfilled Shifts","description":"Note: The current data does not include payroll metrics. However, 29 total unfilled shifts across 5 sites over 30 days likely represents significant unplanned labor cost variance. Request a payroll reconciliation report to understand financial exposure from coverage gaps and any premium pay used to fill shifts ad hoc.","priority":"medium","category":"Payroll & Finance"}],"confidenceScore":0.72,"severityScore":0.82}	56864	2ad7862c-99f0-458e-ac1c-0b05af8da95a	2026-03-11 04:15:13.10214
33d0a343-b1db-4022-8de6-285e888f926c	\N	communication	{"question":"Give me today's executive operational briefing. Cover staffing status, attendance concerns, recruitment pipeline, payroll issues, and site risks. Prioritize by urgency.","assistantTypes":["staffing","attendance","client_risk","recruitment","payroll"]}	{"response":"# WFConnect Executive Operational Briefing\\n**Generated Today | Victoria Hospitality Market & Portfolio**\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ⚠️ IMPORTANT CAVEAT BEFORE YOU READ\\n\\n**Two data integrity issues are affecting this briefing.** First, all payroll time-tracking shows zero actual hours logged against 364 scheduled hours — this is almost certainly a system sync failure, not a real attendance collapse. Second, fill rate is showing 0% across all active sites despite shift activity occurring, suggesting a calculation or data feed error. **Do not make payroll or fill-rate decisions based on these figures until IT investigates.** All other findings below are reliable.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 🔴 CRITICAL — Act Today\\n\\n### 1. Your Recruitment Pipeline Has Effectively Stopped Working\\n\\nThis is your most urgent operational problem. There are **29 unfilled shifts across your portfolio with zero active workers available to fill any of them.** The recruitment pipeline that should be solving this has a health score of **35 out of 100** and has processed exactly zero applications.\\n\\n**What's happening:** One applicant applied 40 days ago for a housekeeper role and has never been reviewed. No one has looked at it. The server role — your largest gap with 21 unfilled shifts — has zero applicants and zero workers. The pipeline isn't slow; it has stopped.\\n\\n**What to do right now:**\\n- **Contact the housekeeper applicant today.** After 40 days, assume they've moved on, but try. Email testcurl@example.com, acknowledge the delay, and fast-track their application if they're still available. This is your only candidate.\\n- **Assign a named person** to own application review with a 48-hour SLA on all new submissions, starting immediately.\\n- **Launch an emergency sourcing push for the server role** — job boards, referral bonuses, staffing agency partners. Target 10+ applications within 7 days. Consider temporary agency staff as a bridge.\\n- **Post targeted listings for housekeeper and supervisor roles** this week. Prioritize supervisor hiring — you need oversight capacity before new hires can be effectively deployed.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2. Hyatt Hotel Is in Serious Trouble\\n\\nHyatt Hotel is your highest-risk site by every measure. It has **21 unfilled shifts over 30 days with a 0% fill rate**, a **23.8% no-show rate** (roughly 5 in every 21 shifts going uncovered), and 273 scheduled hours with no confirmed attendance data. This has been the situation for the full 30-day window with no improvement.\\n\\n**What this means:** Hyatt is likely already operating below safe staffing levels. The client relationship is at risk. If shifts represent active operational needs — not just scheduling placeholders — this site may already be failing to meet its service commitments.\\n\\n**What to do right now:**\\n- **Call the Hyatt site manager today** to confirm whether the 21 unfilled shifts are active operational needs or a scheduling data gap. This distinction determines whether you have a crisis or a reporting problem.\\n- **Schedule an account review with the Hyatt client** to acknowledge the no-show trend and present a corrective action plan before they raise it with you.\\n- **Audit the worker pool assigned to this site** — identify repeat no-show offenders and replace or supplement with higher-reliability workers.\\n- **Implement pre-shift confirmation protocols** (automated reminders 2 hours before shift start) specifically for this site.\\n- **Obtain manual attendance records** from Hyatt supervisors to cover the gap while the payroll data system is being fixed.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 3. Motel 6 Victoria — Complete Service Failure\\n\\nMotel 6 Victoria had one shift. That shift was a no-show. **100% service failure rate.** While the sample is small, a total failure on the only recorded shift is a serious signal — and it carries the highest risk score in your portfolio.\\n\\n**What to do right now:**\\n- **Contact the Motel 6 client today** to acknowledge the failure and confirm their current needs.\\n- **Identify the worker who no-showed**, document the reason, and determine if a reliability action is warranted.\\n- **Assign backup coverage** to this site immediately and confirm all upcoming shifts are covered before you end the day.\\n- **Make a retention call** — a proactive acknowledgment now is far cheaper than losing the client.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 4. Time-Tracking System Is Not Recording Hours — Payroll at Risk\\n\\nAcross all 6 active sites, **zero actual hours have been logged against 364 scheduled hours.** Every site shows the same pattern, which makes this a system failure, not an attendance problem. However, if payroll runs against this data, workers could be paid nothing for hours they actually worked — or scheduled hours could be incorrectly treated as worked hours.\\n\\n**What to do right now:**\\n- **Do not process payroll for this 30-day period** until the data is confirmed accurate.\\n- **Engage IT or your platform administrator today** to audit the clock-in system's connection to the reporting layer. Check whether clock-in events are being captured at the device but failing to sync.\\n- **Instruct all site managers** to maintain manual attendance logs as a backup until the system is fixed.\\n- **Remove the \\"Test Worker\\" account** from production analytics — a test account is contaminating your payroll dataset.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 🟠 HIGH PRIORITY — Act This Week\\n\\n### 5. The Victoria Market Has a Cluster-Wide Staffing Problem\\n\\nFive hospitality sites in Victoria — Hyatt Hotel, Holiday Inn Express, Holiday Inn Victoria, Best Western, and Motel 6 Victoria — are all at 0% fill rates simultaneously. This is not five separate problems. This is one regional problem: likely insufficient worker supply, unattractive shift terms, or a breakdown in how offers are being sent.\\n\\n**Critically: only 3 shift offers have been sent across all sites.** Workers can't fill shifts they're never offered. The offer pipeline appears to be inactive — either automated workflows aren't configured, or no one is manually sending offers.\\n\\n**What to do this week:**\\n- **Manually trigger shift offers for all open positions** at Hyatt, Holiday Inn Express, and Holiday Inn Victoria today.\\n- **Audit the Victoria worker pool** — if there aren't enough qualified workers in the region to cover 5 sites, initiate emergency recruitment: job ads, referral programs, or agency partners within 48–72 hours.\\n- **Review shift terms for positions open 14–30+ days** (particularly Holiday Inn Express). If pay rates or hours are below market, adjust before sending more offers — more outreach won't fix unattractive terms.\\n- **Check whether offer automation is configured and active** for all Victoria sites.\\n\\n### 6. 86% of Your Client Portfolio Is Dormant\\n\\n**32 of 37 registered sites have had zero shift activity** in the current reporting window. This includes high-value properties like Algonquin Resort, Sheraton Four Points Oakville, and CAE Aviation. These clients are either seasonal, paused, using a competitor, or quietly disengaging.\\n\\n**What to do this week:**\\n- **Assign account managers to conduct outreach** to dormant sites, prioritizing high-value properties.\\n- **Categorize each site:** temporarily paused, seasonal, at-risk of churn, or already lost.\\n- **Develop a re-engagement offer** for at-risk accounts before they become confirmed losses.\\n\\n### 7. Fill Rate Data Is Unreliable — Fix Before Next Reporting Cycle\\n\\nThe 0% fill rate showing across all active sites is inconsistent with other data (no-show rates are being calculated, which requires shifts to have been worked). This is likely a calculation error or missing data feed.\\n\\n**Exclude fill rate from any client-facing or executive reporting** until IT confirms the root cause. Decisions made on this metric right now could be wrong.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 🟡 MONITOR — Address Within 2 Weeks\\n\\n### 8. Skyward Building — Watch for Client Disengagement\\n\\nSkyward Building is your only site with a confirmed 100% fill rate and two reliable workers. However, its reliability score dropped 50% from the prior period and it currently shows zero active shifts. This may mean the client has paused — or it may mean they've stopped using the platform.\\n\\n- **Reach out to the Skyward client** to understand the shift in activity and confirm the relationship is intact.\\n- **Document what Skyward is doing right** — 100% fill rate while every other site is at 0% suggests practices worth replicating across the portfolio.\\n\\n### 9. Governance Gaps Are Allowing Problems to Compound\\n\\nMultiple sites have been at 0% fill rate for 30+ days. One applicant has been waiting 40 days without contact. These are not new problems — they're problems that weren't caught early enough.\\n\\n- **Implement automated alerts** for any site falling below 70% fill rate for more than 7 consecutive days.\\n- **Set a 48-hour SLA** for application review and automate an escalation if it's breached.\\n- **Establish a weekly fill rate and pipeline review** at the leadership level.\\n- **Set minimum weekly application volume targets** (suggested: 15–20 per week) as a leading indicator of pipeline health.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## SUMMARY SCORECARD\\n\\n| Area | Status | Trend |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Recruitment Pipeline | 🔴 Critical (35/100) | Stalled |\\n| Hyatt Hotel Staffing | 🔴 Critical | No improvement in 30 days |\\n| Motel 6 Service Delivery | 🔴 Critical | Single failure event |\\n| Victoria Market Fill Rate | 🔴 Critical | Stable at zero |\\n| Payroll Data Integrity | 🔴 Critical | System issue — unresolved |\\n| Portfolio Client Activity | 🟠 High Risk | 86% dormant |\\n| Fill Rate Data Quality | 🟠 High Risk | Anomalous — under investigation |\\n| Skyward Building | 🟡 Watch | Declining activity |\\n| Worker Attendance (active workers) | 🟢 Clean | 100% reliability on record |\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Confidence Note:** Staffing, client risk, and recruitment findings carry 72% confidence. Attendance findings carry 55% confidence due to thin data (2 workers, 1 shift each). Payroll findings are flagged as unreliable pending system investigation. Prioritize the actions above that don't depend on payroll data — they are valid regardless of how the data issue resolves."}	63137	2ad7862c-99f0-458e-ac1c-0b05af8da95a	2026-03-11 04:16:16.244382
