f0c286b6-b786-46ab-8f7f-8fa11bf68817	\N	communication	{"question":"What should I worry about today?","assistantTypes":["staffing","attendance","client_risk"]}	{"response":"# What to Worry About Today\\n\\n## 🔴 Act on These Now\\n\\n### 1. Motel 6 Victoria — A Client You May Be Losing\\nA worker no-showed for the only shift this client has ever had with you, and nothing was done to recover it. They received zero service. **Call them today.** Acknowledge what happened, apologize, and find out if they still want to work with you. If you don't reach out first, they likely won't come back.\\n\\n### 2. Hyatt Hotel — Your Biggest Client Is in Crisis\\nThis is your most urgent operational problem. Hyatt has had **21 shifts posted over the past 30 days and not a single one filled.** On top of that, nearly 1 in 4 shifts that did get scheduled ended in a no-show — and none were recovered. This isn't a bad week; it's been broken for at least a month with no sign of improvement. You need someone owning this account today, reviewing what went wrong, and putting a recovery plan in place.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 🟠 Address This Week\\n\\n### 3. You Have No Way to Recover When Workers Don't Show Up\\nAcross every active site, your fill rate is 0%. That means when a worker no-shows, the shift stays empty. There's no backup system working. Before your next shift cycle, you need to understand why — whether it's a shortage of available workers, a broken notification process, or something else entirely.\\n\\n### 4. Five Hotel Sites Are Completely Dark\\nHoliday Inn Victoria, Best Western, Holiday Inn Express, Motel 6 Victoria, and Hyatt Hotel have all had **zero shifts filled** for 30 days straight, with no improvement. This looks less like five separate problems and more like one: you likely don't have enough workers in the Victoria market to meet demand. Posting more shifts won't fix this — you need to look at your worker supply.\\n\\n### 5. 86% of Your Client Portfolio Is Inactive\\n32 of your 37 active sites have had no shift activity recently. Some may be new accounts still getting started, but others may be quietly disengaging. This is a revenue and relationship risk that deserves a structured review — who's genuinely active, who's stalled, and who needs a check-in call.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 🟡 Keep an Eye On\\n\\n### 6. Skyward Building Went Quiet\\nThis was your only well-performing site — 100% fill rate, reliable workers. But shift activity has dropped to zero and their reliability score has fallen sharply. It may just be a scheduling gap, but it's worth a quick check to confirm the relationship is still on track.\\n\\n### 7. Your Attendance Data Is Too Thin to Trust\\nOnly 2 workers have been tracked for reliability, each with just 1 shift. The numbers look perfect, but they don't mean much yet. Don't let a clean report create a false sense of security — you don't have enough data to draw real conclusions here.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## The One-Line Summary\\n**Your core problem today is Hyatt Hotel and Motel 6 Victoria — one client got no service at all, and your largest active site has been broken for a month. Everything else flows from the same root cause: not enough workers in Victoria to fill the shifts you're selling.**"}	19967	2ad7862c-99f0-458e-ac1c-0b05af8da95a	2026-03-11 05:08:19.232973
