a06cfe62-9e51-4321-b01e-82e8e7729309	2ad7862c-99f0-458e-ac1c-0b05af8da95a	assistant	**There are currently no unfilled shifts in the immediate 12, 24, or 48-hour windows. However, 5 sites have a 0% fill rate across 7, 14, and 30-day periods, indicating a systemic staffing pipeline issue rather than an acute scheduling gap.**\n\n**Key Findings:**\n- No Unfilled Shifts in Upcoming 48-Hour Window: The unfilled shifts data shows zero open shifts in the next 12, 24, and 48 hours. There are no immediate coverage emergencies requiring urgent action at this time.\n- 5 Sites Have 0% Fill Rate Over Extended Periods [CRITICAL]: Despite no unfilled shifts appearing in the near-term window, HOLIDAY INN VICTORIA, Holiday Inn Express, Best Western, Motel 6 Victoria, and Hyatt Hotel all show 0% fill rates across 7, 14, and 30-day periods. This suggests shifts at these sites are either not being created/posted in the system, or there is a data pipeline issue.\n- Hyatt Hotel Has the Largest Volume of Unfilled Shifts [CRITICAL]: Hyatt Hotel has 21 total shifts over the 14 and 30-day periods with 0 filled — the highest absolute volume of any problematic site. This represents the greatest operational exposure if these shifts are active.\n- Low Shift Offer Acceptance Rate: Only 1 out of 3 shift offers was accepted (33% acceptance rate). While the sample size is very small, this low acceptance rate may be contributing to unfilled positions at the problematic sites.\n\n**Risks:**\n- Possible Data Gap Masking True Unfilled Shift Count (medium likelihood, critical impact): The combination of 0 unfilled shifts in the next 48 hours alongside persistent 0% fill rates over 30 days across 5 sites is unusual. It is possible that shifts exist but are not surfacing correctly in the unfilled shift feed, meaning real coverage gaps may be going undetected.\n- Hyatt Hotel Operational Risk (high likelihood, critical impact): With 21 shifts at 0% fill over 30 days and no improvement trend, Hyatt Hotel faces significant risk of understaffing if these shifts are active and workers are not being successfully assigned.\n- Shift Offer Pipeline Inefficiency (medium likelihood, medium impact): A 33% acceptance rate on shift offers means 2 out of 3 offers did not result in a filled shift. If this trend continues at scale, fill rates will remain low even as more offers are sent.\n\n**Recommended Actions:**\n- Verify Unfilled Shift Data Integrity [URGENT]: Investigate why 5 sites show 0% fill rates over 30 days while the unfilled shift feed shows zero open shifts in the next 48 hours. Confirm whether shifts are being posted correctly and whether the data pipeline is functioning as expected. This discrepancy should be resolved before drawing further conclusions.\n- Prioritize Hyatt Hotel Staffing Review [URGENT]: With 21 shifts at 0% fill over 30 days, conduct an immediate review of Hyatt Hotel's shift postings, worker pool availability, and offer history to determine why no shifts are being filled.\n- Investigate Low Shift Offer Acceptance Rate [HIGH]: Review the 3 shift offers sent — identify which sites they were for, why 2 were not accepted, and whether offer timing, pay rates, or worker availability are contributing factors.\n- Expand Worker Pool for Problematic Sites [HIGH]: For HOLIDAY INN VICTORIA, Holiday Inn Express, Best Western, Motel 6 Victoria, and Hyatt Hotel, review whether enough qualified workers are being invited to shifts. Consider broadening eligibility criteria or recruiting additional workers for these locations.\n- Monitor Fill Rate Trends Weekly: All 5 problematic sites show a 'stable' trend at 0% — meaning there is no improvement over time. Set up weekly review checkpoints to track whether interventions are having an effect.	{"assistantsInvoked":["staffing"],"overallSeverity":0.75,"metadata":{"totalDurationMs":29740,"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6"}}	2026-03-11 05:06:06.534938
