24b7d617-c5f9-4cc1-81dd-9ab624b67519	2ad7862c-99f0-458e-ac1c-0b05af8da95a	assistant	**Across the 30-day analysis period, both active workers maintain perfect reliability scores of 100 with zero late arrivals, no-shows, or cancellations. The workforce is very small (2 workers, 1 shift each), so while the data is clean, it provides limited statistical basis for deep risk assessment.**\n\n**Key Findings:**\n- Perfect Reliability Across All Workers: Both Test Worker and Bergel Sarenas achieved a composite reliability score of 100/100, with zero incidents of lateness, no-shows, or accept-then-cancel behaviour in the past 30 days.\n- Extremely Low Shift Volume: Each worker completed only 1 shift in the 30-day period. With such a small sample size, perfect scores carry limited predictive weight — a single future incident would significantly impact reliability metrics.\n- No Reliability Trend Data Available: There are no historical trend records or declining worker signals in the dataset. It is not possible to assess whether current performance represents improvement, consistency, or a new baseline.\n- Single Site, Single Role Coverage: All activity is concentrated at one site (Skyward Building) and one role type (Housekeeper). There is no cross-site or cross-role data to benchmark against or identify site-specific risk patterns.\n\n**Risks:**\n- Insufficient Data for Reliable Risk Prediction (medium likelihood, medium impact): With only 2 workers each having completed 1 shift, the dataset is too small to identify meaningful attendance patterns. A single no-show or late arrival in the next period would represent a 100% incident rate for that worker, potentially triggering false alarms.\n- No Redundancy in Workforce Coverage (low likelihood, high impact): With only 2 workers assigned to Skyward Building, any attendance failure — even a single no-show — would leave the site critically understaffed with no buffer capacity.\n- Absence of Trend Visibility (medium likelihood, medium impact): No reliability trend data exists, meaning early warning signals of worker disengagement or declining performance cannot currently be detected. Issues may only become visible after they have already escalated.\n\n**Recommended Actions:**\n- Expand Workforce at Skyward Building: With only 2 workers covering a single site, there is no resilience against absences. Recruit or assign at least 1-2 additional workers to Skyward Building to ensure coverage continuity if an attendance issue arises.\n- Increase Shift Volume to Build Reliable Baselines: Reliability scores based on 1 shift per worker are not statistically meaningful. Aim to schedule workers for a minimum of 5-10 shifts before drawing conclusions about their reliability profile.\n- Enable Historical Trend Tracking [HIGH]: Ensure the system is capturing shift-level attendance data over time so that reliability trends can be computed in future periods. Early trend detection is critical for proactive intervention.\n- Conduct Proactive Check-In with Both Workers: While performance is currently perfect, a brief engagement check-in with Test Worker and Bergel Sarenas can help identify any early concerns, confirm availability for upcoming shifts, and reinforce positive attendance behaviour.	{"assistantsInvoked":["attendance"],"overallSeverity":0.05,"metadata":{"totalDurationMs":26780,"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6"}}	2026-03-11 05:06:43.49465
